The effect oi the second lex Publilia, according to Livy, was ‘ut legum quae comitiis centuriatis ferrentur ante initum suffragium patres auctores lierent;' it thus merely reaffirmed the constitutional doctrine, that no bill should be submitted to the centuries, with a view to its becoming law, unless it had been previously approved hythe senate. lt is clear lrom Cicero thatin his time the Servian centurial constitu- tion had undergone considerable alterations, effected by in some way combining the centurial organization with that ol the tribes.
